1 ARMA model identification

1.1 Mathematics behind ARMA model identification

Consider \[X_t -\phi_1 X_{t-1}-\dots-\phi_p X_{t-p}= a_t +\theta_1 a_{t-1}+ \dots + \theta_q a_{t-q}, ~~~a_t \sim NID(0,\sigma^2_a),~~~(1)\] where \(NID(0,\sigma^2_a)\) denotes IID normal random variable with mean zero and variable \(\sigma^2\). Note that in this document we assume \(a_t\sim NID(0,\sigma^2_a)\) unless you are told otherwise.

1.1.2 Theoretical PACF of \(AR(p)\) processes

  1. What is PACF?
    The partial autocorreltion function (PACF) is usually defined as conditional correlation and given by \(Corr(X_t,X_{t+k}|X_{t+1},\dots,X_{t+k-1})\).

1.2 Use R to check your answers

  • Calculate theoretical ACF and PACF of an ARMA model in r
    ARMAacf(ar = numeric(), ma = numeric(), lag.max = r, pacf = FALSE)
    Â Â Â Â 

1.2.1 Theoretical ACF and PACF of AR(1) process

# Theoretical ACF and PACF of AR(1) process
ar.acf<-zapsmall(ARMAacf(ar = 0.5, lag.max = 5))[-1]
ar.pacf = zapsmall(ARMAacf(ar = 0.5, lag.max = 5, pacf = TRUE))
ar.df <- data.frame(ACF = ar.acf, PACF = ar.pacf, lag = 1:5)
p1<- ggplot(data = ar.df, aes (x = lag, y = ACF))+
        geom_bar(stat = "identity")+
        geom_text(aes(label = ACF), vjust = 2, size =2, color = "white")+
        theme_minimal()+ggtitle("ACF")
p2<- ggplot(data = ar.df, aes (x = lag, y = PACF))+
        geom_bar(stat = "identity")+
        geom_text(aes(label = PACF), vjust = 2, size =2, color = "white")+
        theme_minimal()+ggtitle("PACF")
grid.arrange(p1,p2, nrow = 1)

1.3 Rule of thumb

The following table is taken from Table 6.1 of Wei (2006).

ACF PACF
\(AR(p)\) Tails off or damped sine wave Cut off after lag \(p\)
\(MA(q)\) Cut off after lag \(q\) Tails off or damped sine wave
\(ARMA(p,q)\) Tails off after lag \((q-p)\) Tails off after lag \((p-q)\)

2 Checking statioanrity of ARMA models

2.1 Stationarity of ARMA models

  • How can we tell if a given ARMA model is stationary?
    Show that a given ARMA model satisfying the definition of weak stationarity.

Â Â Â Â 

  • A general approach to test stationarity of an ARMA model
    Consider an \(ARMA(p,q)\) model \[\phi(B) X_t = \theta(B) a_t,~~~(7)\] where \[\phi(B) =1-\phi_1 B-\phi_2 B^2-\dots - \phi_p X_{t-p},~~~(8)\] \[\theta(B) = 1+ \theta_1 B +\dots +\theta_q B^q,~~~(9)\] and \(B^k X_t = X_{t-k}\) is the backward shift operator.

Â Â Â Â 

  • If an ARMA process defined in Equation (7) is statioanry, all roots in \(\phi(B)\) must lie outside a unit circle.

2.2 Simulated examples

Consider the following simulated ARMA processes

\[X_t - 0.5 X_{t-1} = a_t, ~~~ a_t \sim NID(0,1)\] \[X_t = a_t + 0.7 a_{t-1}, ~~~ a_t\sim NID(0,1)\]

\[X_t -0.5 X_{t-1}= a_t + 0.7 a_{t-1}, ~~~ a_t \sim NID(0,1)\]

# Simulated time series
set.seed(1234)
ar1 = arima.sim(list(order = c(1,0,0), ar = 0.5), n = 200)
ma1 = arima.sim(list(order = c(0,0,1), ma = 0.7), n = 200)
arma11 = arima.sim(list(order = c(1,0,1), ar = 0.5, ma = 0.7), n = 200)
autoplot(cbind(ar1, ma1, arma11))+
  ggtitle("Simulated stationary time series")+
  theme_minimal()+
  ylab("")+theme(legend.position="bottom")

3 Causal and invertible representation of an ARMA model

3.1 Definition

  • An ARMA model is a causal process if it can be expressed as a stationary MA(\(\infty\)) process \[ X_t = \sum^\infty_{i=0} \psi_i a_{t-i}.~~~~(10) \]

Â Â Â Â 

  • An ARMA model is an invertible process if it can be expressed as a stationary AR(\(\infty\)) process \[ X_t - \sum^\infty_{i=1} \pi_i X_{t-i} = a_t.~~~~(11) \]

Â Â Â Â 

  • We can use r to calculate \(\Psi\) coefficients.

3.2 Examples

3.2.1 Stationary ARMA model

Consider the simulated ARMA(1,1) process discussed earlier.

coef(mod.arma11)%>%
  kable(digits = 3, caption = "Simulated stationary ARMA(1,1) model")
Simulated stationary ARMA(1,1) model
x
ar1 0.462
ma1 0.749
intercept -0.115 
psi = ImpulseCoefficientsARMA(phi = mod.arma11$model$phi, 
                              theta = mod.arma11$model$theta, 
                              lag.max = 10)%>%
  round(digits = 3)

psi.df = data.frame(lag = 0:(length(psi)-1), psi = psi)

ggplot(data = psi.df, aes (x = lag, y = psi))+
        geom_bar(stat = "identity", alpha =0.3)+
        geom_text(aes(label = psi), vjust = 1, size =2, color = "black")+
        theme_minimal()+ggtitle("Psi coefficients")

3.2.2 Nonstionary ARMA model

Consider the following ARMA model \[X_t - 1.2 X_{t-1} = a_t + 0.5 a_{t-1}.\]

psi = ImpulseCoefficientsARMA(phi = 1.2, 
                              theta = 0.5, 
                              lag.max = 10)%>%
  round(digits = 3)

psi.df = data.frame(lag = 0:(length(psi)-1), psi = psi)

ggplot(data = psi.df, aes (x = lag, y = psi))+
        geom_bar(stat = "identity", alpha =0.3)+
        geom_text(aes(label = psi), vjust = 1, size =2, color = "black")+
